4":"1534","1500":"1500","1455":"1455","1488":"1488","1477":"1477","1564":"1564","1541":"1541","1475":"1475","1486":"1486","1529":"1529","Bethersden, Kent, England, United Kingdom":"Bethersden, Kent, England, United Kingdom",",, of Kent, England":"Kent, England, United Kingdom","Bletchingley, Surrey, England":"Bletchingley, Surrey, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Margarete","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["from Greek.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margaret","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]},{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretha","meanings":["from Greek.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margarethe","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Margarete was born about 1477, in Kent, England, United Kingdom, her father, John Snelling, was 28 and her mother, Joan Coddington, was 23. She had at least 1 son and 1 daughter with Stephen Shawe."},"et":{"Abt 1477–":"umbes 1477–Surnud","1477–Female":"1477–Surnud","1486–1564":"1486–1564","1488–Female":"1488–Surnud","1500–1570":"1500–1570","1475–Male":"1475–Surnud","1500–1541":"1500–1541","–Male":"Surnud","1450–1529":"1450–1529","1455–1534":"1455–1534","1 July 1485":"1. juuli 1485","1450":"1450","1570":"1570","Abt 1477":"umbes 1477","1534":"1534","1500":"1500","1455":"1455","1488":"1488","1477":"1477","1564":"1564","1541":"1541","1475":"1475","1486":"1486","1529":"1529","Bethersden, Kent, England, United Kingdom":"Bethersden, Kent, Inglismaa, United Kingdom",",, of Kent, England":"Kent, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Bletchingley, Surrey, England":"Bletchingley, Surrey, England"},"fi":{"Abt 1477–":"noin 1477–Kuollut","1477–Female":"1477–Kuollut","1486–1564":"1486–1564","1488–Female":"1488–Kuollut","1500–1570":"1500–1570","1475–Male":"1475–Kuollut","1500–1541":"1500–1541","–Male":"Kuollut","1450–1529":"1450–1529","1455–1534":"1455–1534","1 Ju